I was looking for a convenient way to build a `Iterable` for a collection of `Iterable`s and tried `Iterables.concat(Iterable<? extends Iterable<? extends T>> inputs)` (v25.1)

My expectation is that this is functionally equivalent to iterating all `Iterable`s and appending all the elements into a new collection that is the merged `Iterable` (just without creating an actual intermediate collection). This does not seamed to be true as it was failing my tests both due to lack of expected elements and throwing `NoSuchElementException` unexpectedly. Building the intermediate collection works fine. 

To cross check I wrote a naive version myself that looks like this:

```
final Iterable<Iterable<String>> sources = ....
return new Iterable<String>() {

            @Override
            public Iterator<String> iterator() {
                return new Iterator<String>() {

                    Iterator<Iterable<String>> iter = sources.iterator();
                    Iterator<String> cur;

                    @Override
                    public boolean hasNext() {
                        if (cur == null && !iter.hasNext())
                            return false;
                        if (cur == null)
                            cur = iter.next().iterator();
                        while (!cur.hasNext()) {
                            if (!iter.hasNext())
                                return false;
                            cur = iter.next().iterator();
                        }
                        return true;
                    }

                    @Override
                    public String next() {
                        if (cur == null)
                            throw new NoSuchElementException();
                        return cur.next();
                    }
                };
            }
        };
```
This also has the expected behavior. So I cannot put my finger on what goes wrong with `Iterables.concat` but it surely is not transparent. Or I misunderstand its use case.

`Streams.concat` functions as expected when its arguments are finite streams.
If we concat two streams: the first is finite and the second is infinite, then obviously we get an infinite stream. But we can iterate over a limited number of elements. This is the scenario where the program hangs.

```java
import com.google.common.collect.Streams;

import java.util.PrimitiveIterator;
import java.util.stream.IntStream;

public class MyMain {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        IntStream stream123 = IntStream.of(1, 2, 3);
        IntStream stream4567 = IntStream.of(4, 5, 6, 7);
        IntStream stream1234567 = Streams.concat(stream123, stream4567);
        printFirstElements(stream1234567, 5);
        // output:
        // 1
        // 2
        // 3
        // 4
        // 5



        IntStream streamInfinite99 = IntStream.generate(() -> 99);
        printFirstElements(streamInfinite99, 3);
        // output:
        // 99
        // 99
        // 99

        IntStream stream123AndThenInfinite77 = Streams.concat(IntStream.of(1, 2, 3), IntStream.generate(() -> 77));
        printFirstElements(stream123AndThenInfinite77, 5);
        // output:
        // 1
        // 2
        // 3
        // and then program hangs
    }

    static void printFirstElements(IntStream stream, int count) {
        int counter = 0;
        for (PrimitiveIterator.OfInt iterator = stream.iterator(); iterator.hasNext(); ) {
            Integer next = iterator.next();
            System.out.println(next);
            counter++;
            if (counter == count) {
                break;
            }
        }
    }
}
```

I often have to write the following kind of code. This code isn't as obvious as people first think. I've seen many new coders hit with this very hard and they spend countless time trying to figure out an appropriate way to implement this.

    void doSomething(List<A> listOfAs, B b) {
      // somehow call doSomething(a, b) with each element of listOfAs as a.
    }
    void doSomething(A a, B b) {
      // use both a and b
    }

Here are a few possible implementations of the "somehow" comment.

1. 

    void doSomething(List<A> listOfAs, B b) {
      listOfAs.forEach(a -> doSomething(a, b));
    }

2. 

    void doSomething(List<A> listOfAs, B b) {
      for (A a: listOfAs) {
        doSomething(a, b);
      }
    }

3. 

    Consumer<A> doSomethingWithFixedB(B b) {
      return a -> doSomething(a, b);
    }
    void doSomething(List<A> listOfAs, B b) {
      listOfAs.forEach(doSomethingWithFixedB(b));
    }

What I suggest is to generalize the last case, which seems the most portable way of handling this feature.

    public static <A, B> Consumer<B> bindFirst(BiConsumer<A, B> biConsumer, A first) {
      return last -> biConsumer.accept(first, last);
    }
    public static <A, B> Consumer<A> bindLast(BiConsumer<A, B> biConsumer, B last) {
      return first -> biConsumer.accept(first, last);
    }

This way, people can call the methods like this:

    void doSomething(List<A> listOfAs, B b) {
      listOfAs.forEach(Consumers.bindLast(this::doSomething, b));
    }

I'm not saying it's absolutely clearer than the first example I gave, but it's more explicit and intuitive for newcomers, from my experience as a developer team-lead.

