One of the best features of `java.util.Optional` is the ability to call `.ifPresent` on it, executing an action only if the Optional is populated: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/Optional.html#ifPresent-java.util.function.Consumer-

Guava's Optional has no equivalent. Currently, there are 3 ways to achieve this behavior, from what I can tell:

1) Just manually unwrap the object. The most sane way, in my opinion, but very non-functional.
```
if (optional.isPresent()) {
  T optionalUnwrapped = optional.get();
  ...
}
```

2) Use `.transform` and do your side-effect-performing code in there, and just `return this` at the end. This is not semantically correct and will probably cause confusion for readers of the code.

3) Write a static utility method that looks something like `Optionals.ifPresent(optional, (value) -> ...);`. Unfortunately this is not as fluent as a method on `Optional`, and would be duplicated across projects.

I'd imagine the implementation would be as simple as:

```
public void ifPresent(Consumer<? super T> action) {
  if (isPresent()) {
    action.call(get());
  }
}
```

